{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600520/1930121201/0351.xml":{"full_text":"A-12\nINSURANCE ASSETS\nINCREASE IN 1930\n\nMead of Concern Predicts Ad\ndition of $1,418,000,000\nDespite Depression.\n8r the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. December 12.\u2014Addi\ntion of $1,418,000,000 to the assets of\nlife insurance companies in the United\nStates this year, despite the business\ndepression, was forecast today by Wal\nton L. Crocker, president of the John\nHancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. of\nBoston, before the Association of Life\nInsurance Presidents.\nThis sum, he said, will bring total\ninvestments of the companies to $lB,-\n900.000,000 at the end of the year.\n\u201cThe assets at the end of this year,\u201d\nhe declared, \u201cwill be double those held\n\u2022even years ago and will be equal to\nmore than three times the assets held\nat the end of 1917.\u201d\nThe figures he presented were com\npiled in a survey of 52 companies\nrepresenting 91.8 per cent of the total\nassets of all United States legal re\n\u2022erve life insurance companies.\nReal estate mortgages, representing\nthe leading investment medium of life\nInsurance companies, comprise 40.3 per\ncent of their total assets, J* said, ag\ngregating $6,994,000,000. Bonds and\nstocks, with a total of $6,531,000,000, or\n37.6 per cent, are second in investment\nImportance.\n\u201cThe whole exhibit,\u201d Crocker sum\nmed up, \u201cis an assurance, were any\nheeded, that the funds of the life in\nsurance companies are stable to the\nhighest degree.\"\nRECOUNT SOUGHT\nWITH CONGRESS AID\nOklahoman Defeated by Democrat\nin First District, Wires Sep- j\nresentative O\u2019Connor. j\nWt the Associated Press.\nMIAMI, Okla., December 12.\u20140. P.\nMason, Miami attorney, said yesterday I\nhe had telegraphed Representative\nCharles O'Connor. Republican, in\nWashington, advisihg him to seek in j\nCongress a recount of last November\u2019s\nelection, in which he was defeated in\nthe first Oklahoma district by Wesley\nDisney, Democrat.\nMason, who was interested in the\nsheriff's race recount in Ottawa County,\n\u00a3ch resulted in reversing results and\nwing the Republican candidate to\nbe the leader, said O\u2019Connor would gain\nenough votes in the county to overcome\nDisney's lead in the district if a recount\nwere made.\nOfficial returns of the State election\nboard gave Disney a lead of 360 in the\ndistrict and 467 in Ottawa County.\nThe time for filing a contest in the\nState has expired.\nSWEDISH SHIP SAVES\nSINKING VESSEL\u2019S CREW\nSchooner Amy G. McKean Beached\nlust in Time 800 Miles\nFrom Queenstown.\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, December 12.\u2014A message\nto Lloyds last night reported that the\nSwedish steamer Strassa had rescued\nthe crew of the schooner Amy G. Mc-\nKean, bound from Swansea for Halifax,\nas the latter vessel was foundering in\nthe Atlantic 800 miles from Queenstown.\nThe disabled schooner was set afire\nafter the crew had been taken off to\nprevent her becoming a menance to\nnavigation. The message did not disclose\nthe cause of the trouble or the number\nrescued.\nBOOTLEGGING IN TURKEY\nIS APPLIED TO RADIOS\nThousand Culprits Caught in Year\nCharged With Clandestinely Ap\npropriating Government Monopoly.\nBy the Associated Press\nISTANBUL, Turkey, December 12.\nIn Turkey it\u2019s radio that's bootlegged.\nA thousand culprits have been caught\nIn the last year.\nRadio is a monopoly of the govern\nment, and the clandestine listener-in\nwho neglects to pay the required tax,\nor who buys his set from somebody\nother than the monopoly, is subject to\nheavy fine.\nBANDIT SLAYS GROCER\nStore Manager Had Refused to\nTurn Over Day\u2019s Receipts.\nNEW YORK, December 12\nfusal to turn over the day\u2019s receipts to\na hold-up man cost Michael McLaugh\nlin, 32. manager of a chain grocery\nstore, his life last night. A bullet\npenetrated McLaughlin\u2019s head and he\ndied soon after being taken to a hos\npital. The slayer escaped.\na _.j!\n(AHAM jf\nX Borneo\notscE ooctht\n7b KNOW\nENOUGH TO\nLEAVE RRE.\nA woman who sees the magical\ntransformation a little paint will\nmake in an old worivlooking piece\ni mi furniture wants to brighten up\n\u202211 the odds and ends around the\nhouse. Try some of the new quick*\ndrying brushing lacquer You can\nhave \u201cnew\u201d furniture at very little\ncost. Our water and oil color boxes\nmake excellent gifts.\n\u25a0\u2022Waher\\for^n^\nactsVaw&n materials\nIV I 4.21 TCNTM STttCT.NV\nWASHINGTON. DC.\u2019\nNATIOSIAC 76d&\nL\nMERRIE ENGLAND IMPORTS U. S.\nIDEA AND CALLS IT 'MOBILE POLICE\u2019\nV- f v\nJob of New Force Is to Get Order and Decent Conduct\non King\u2019s Highways.\n....-1..\nBy the Associated Press.\nLONDON, December 12. \u2014England is\nimporting an American institution and\ndoesn\u2019t quite know fohat to call it.\nNew road rules, in force January 1,\nwill bring 1,000 police on motor cycles\nand in cars, besides an additional force\nfor London alone.\nIn America, of course, they are speed\ncops; but over here the slang is quoted\nand the newspapers have compromised\nby referring to the proposed force as\n\u201cmolglle police.\u201d\nSaid Herbert Morrison, the minister\nof transport, in a statement reassuring\nEnglish motorists:\n\u201cI have never been in America and\nI cannot speak with any authority as to\nthe practices of what are known as\n\u2018speed cops\u2019 in America, but I have no\nwish that our police should act in a\nvindictive or bullying spirit.\n\u201cThe job of the mobile police is to\naim at getting order, considerateness\nand decent conduct on the King\u2019s high\nways.\n\u201cThere will be cases where the police\nGive an g\n3 Atwater\n1 Kent Radio\nThis\nChristmas\n|h.w.higham\u00a3\nI# 10S B St. S.E.\nv a Line. 0647\nGive an\nATWATER KENT\nB Hand-matched butt walnut\nfront panels beautify this de-\nlightful model with the Gold\nen Voice. A most desirable\nLowboy Complete\n$139.20\nV\nMain 920\n2 m 7^